<br>
The EQ2 screenshots are old, but they all suffer from the same flaw: harsh directional lighting, overuse of detail and bump maps, oversharp shadows, and a &quot;gloss/plastic&quot; look that makes things look exactly like CGI monsters trying to be real.<br>
<br>
Whereas the WoW graphics don't try to look real at all; they recognize that the environment is fantastic (in the sense of fantasy), and instead show reasonably appealling graphics, that will perform well on a much wider variety of systems, without trying to make things look hyper realistic (and failing).<br>
<br>
I have exactly the same issues with Doom3, for example.<br>
<br>
They make use of all this wonderful technology, and in trying to look super realistic, fall completely short of the mark.  <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Don't get me wrong.  The models and textures are rich and detailed.  They just look more &quot;wrong&quot; than the cartoonlike look of WoW.<br>
<br>
The real thing is, game engines aren't really as necessary as people like to make them out to be.  Halflife was lauded as a great game not because of it's engine, but because of the content.  Look at the tech demos from E3 for Halflife2, and compare to Doom3.  Doom3 is all glitz and show, whereas HL2 looks pretty but also seems to have a much richer and more interactive world.<br>
<br>
The screenshots of EQ2 make me fear that more attention is being paid to trying to squeeze and use every DX9+ feature into the game, instead of adding to the actual content and gameplay instead.<br>
<br>
I'd much rather have 2 playable, moderately modelled and detailed dungeons than one really hyperrealistic dungeon that requires a 4Gz cpu and an nv50 card to render.<br>
<br>
An aesthetic presentation of a fantasy world is not contingent upon a flashy rendering engine.  That is the crux of why WoW graphics work for me more than EQ2.<br>
<br>
This of course, may all change by the time EQ2 and WoW are released.<br>
<br>
-- Hika<br>
